    "summary": "No -- keep First/Second/Zeroth, avoid \"Ultimate\"",
    "content": "No. Keep First Reality, Second Reality, Zeroth Reality.\n\n**Against \"Ultimate Reality\" for 第一实在.** The author explicitly warns in footnote 25 that 第一实在 is a name (名称), not an ontological claim about what is most real. \"Ultimate Reality\" is *precisely* the term used throughout the Western metaphysical tradition for the very thing the author is dismantling -- the 终极实在, the unreachable ground that the author argues was always constructed upward from phenomena. Calling phenomena \"Ultimate Reality\" would create a direct terminological collision: the reader would confuse the author's 第一实在 (phenomena as epistemological starting point) with the traditional 终极实在 (the metaphysical ground the author rejects). The whole point of the author's numbering system is to be neutral and positional -- First means \"where we start,\" not \"what is most real.\"\n\n**Against \"Secondary\" for 第二实在.** \"Secondary\" in English carries a strong connotation of \"lesser, derivative, inferior\" -- as in \"secondary source,\" \"secondary importance.\" The author's 第二实在 (the objective world as model/interpretation of phenomena) is not inferior to 第一实在; it is simply the next layer of construction. \"Second\" is neutral and positional; \"Secondary\" is evaluative. The author is deliberately avoiding value judgments about which reality is \"more real.\"\n\n**The ordinal numbering is the author's deliberate design choice.** Zeroth, First, Second -- this is the language of mathematical indexing, which fits the author's structural-formal approach. It says: here is a sequence, here is a starting point, here are the layers built upon it. Replacing this with evaluative English terms undermines the neutrality the author worked to establish.\n\nKeep the footnotes to explain the roles, but let the names stay clean and ordinal."
